values:
I'm doing this because one of my favorite people on earth did it first, and I think it's always good to reflect on where you are, where you were, and where you want to go.

<lj-cut>1. What did you do in 2015 that you'd never done before?
Said a final goodbye to my dad.

2. Did you keep your new years' resolutions, and will you make more for next year?
There were no resolutions this year, and that in itself was liberating.

3. Did anyone close to you give birth?
No.

4. Did anyone close to you die?
Yes.

5. What countries did you visit?
Many, many in many of the books I read. London of the late 1800's was my favorite.

6. What would you like to have in 2016 that you lacked in 2015?
More money would be very, very nice.

7. What dates from 2015 will remain etched upon your memory, and why?
January 6. That's the day the most important man in my life died. 

8. What was your biggest achievement of the year?
I survived what I thought I couldn't.

9. What was your biggest failure? 
I don't think there were actual failures this year. Rejected Manuscripts were a life lesson. One I'd just as soon not repeat!

10. Did you suffer illness or injury?
Nothing new, knock on wood.

11. What was the best thing you bought?
The books I've read.

12. Whose behavior merited celebration? 
My children~!  Ah, such wonderful grown ups I accidentally raised!

13. Whose behavior made you appalled and depressed?
Several presidential candidates. ISIS. Bill Cosby.

14. Where did most of your money go?
Essentials. Thank God for the friends who know how much I need to read!

15. What did you get really, really, really excited about?
Christmas. Seeing Star Wars with my kids. THAT was epic.

16. What song will always remind you of 2015?
Hello by Adele

17. Compared to this time last year, are you: 
a) happier or sadder? Happier
b) thinner or fatter? Thinner
c) richer or poorer? I think this one is a wash.

18. What do you wish you'd done more of?
Spent time with Cindy. Write. 

19. What do you wish you'd done less of?
Grieved, but I don't think you get to choose how much or how little of this you do.

20. How did you spend Christmas?
With my children. It was the best Christmas in years.

21. What was your favorite month of 2015?
December

22. Did you fall in love in 2015?
Yes. With the Magpie Lord. (Thank you, KJ Charles, for Lucien Crane).

23. How many one-night stands?
Oh, please. Who has the energy?

24. What was your favorite TV program?
Hmmm. Not much of a tv fan, honestly. The Chew?

25. Do you hate anyone now that you didn't hate this time last year? 
No. Again, who has the energy for this?

26. What was the best book you read?
Oh, so many.
The Magpie Lord series by KJ Charles.
Maelstrom by Jordan L. Hawk
The Couple Next Door by Rick R. Reed
The Secret Casebook of Simon Feximal by KJ Charles.
Wide Awake by Nick Nolan
Bitter Taffy by Amy Lane
Lonely Hearts by Heidi Cullinan

27. What was your greatest musical discovery?
I think it was more a matter of re-discovery. Mannehiem Steamroller creates perfect background music for writing.

28. What did you want and get?
A new Coffee maker!!

29. What did you want and not get?
A new contract.

30. What was your favorite film of this year?
Star Wars: The Force Awakens

31. What did you do on your birthday, and how old were you?
Sat home and read. And 58. (Earning my senior discount, one day at a time!!)

32. What one thing would have made your year immeasurably more satisfying?
Getting a contract. Lol.

33. How would you describe your personal fashion concept in 2015?
What's a fashion concept?

34. What kept you sane?
My kids.

35. Which celebrity/public figure did you fancy the most?
Donald Trump. Dig the comb over. (I'm lying) Uhm... Taylor Kinney.

36. What political issue stirred you the most?
The SCOTUS ruling on marriage equality.

37. Who did you miss?
My Dad. My husband. My first Prince Charming.

39. Tell us a valuable life lesson you learned in 2015.
Don't try to rush grief. It's over when it's over.

40. Quote a song lyric that sums up your year.
Sometimes I wish that I could freeze the picture
And save it from the funny tricks of time
Slipping through my fingers
Slipping through my fingers all the time</lj-cut>

Every year I participate in HD Erised's holiday gift exchange, and my gift posted a couple of days ago. It's 45k, so I had to read it in pieces, but OMG you guys; it's so lovely! It features a Draco who is more than a decade down the road from Hogwarts, the father of a first year himself. He's a man who has done everything he thought he had to do restore some sense of honor to the family name, at the cost of his happiness. But he's so in love with his son, and so wrapped up in making sure Scorpius has everything he needs, he doesn't realize he's miserable until Scorpius has left for school and he's more alone than he's ever been in his life. I wanted to wrap my arms around him and tell him everything was going to be okay.

This fic features grown men Harry and Draco. They had <i>a thing</i> as Harry so aptly describes it, before Draco got married, but that's been long ago. Now Draco runs a non profit to benefit the widows and orphans of the war with his best friend, Pansy, and Harry is the flying Professor at Hogwarts. Pansy and Draco are embroiled in plans for a gala for the foundation when Draco gets a letter from Professor Potter, telling him Scorpius is having trouble flying. Which is mystifying, because Scorpius has been a prodigy on a broom since he sat his little butt on one at three. This leads to revelations on both of their parts, but we see them from inside of Draco's head. His poor, miserable, confused head. 

There is wonderful original magic here *you'll never think of ice cream the same way again, I promise*, a mouthy, saucy, sassy best friend, and Draco who is insecure about everything but fatherhood, which he's very good at, and a grown up Professor Potter who is sex on legs. Seriously, when Draco sees him fresh from a shower, with damp hair wearing sweats and t-shirt and a towel hanging around his neck, you can almost lean in and smell the fresh scent of soap on his skin. 

This is a beautifully written, smart, insightful fic, and I loved it. Make some cocoa, curl up in front of a fire, and read this lovely piece. It's one of the nicest presents I've ever received.

<a href="http://hd-erised.livejournal.com/48805.html">Expectations (And Their Undoing)

I haven't been around much lately. Truth is, I've had my li'l nose to the grindstone and my agent has a novel I finished in September. I'm excited about it; it's book one of a 'blue collar romance' series, and I'm anxious to see it find a home. Right now I'm fleshing out a Christmas novella that I submitted as a short story. Both my agent and I feel like 18000 just wasn't long enough to tell the story the way I wanted to. So, I'm finishing that up over the next ten days. Then, for the first time in a couple of years, I'm doing NaNoWriMo!!!  If anyone would like to be writing buddies, I'm Diana Copland over there. Look me up and give me a poke! I'm going to be writing my next novel, the sequel to A Reason To Believe, and I'm excited to get back to Matt and Kiernan after all this time. 

Anywho, if you're going to be there, lets do it together!!

Title: The Gift Author: oldenuf2nb Characters: Harry/Draco Rating: PG-13 Warning(s): None Word count: 5,297 Disclaimer: Characters are the property of JK Rowling, et al. This fic/drabble was written for fun, not for profit. Written for: slythindor100 Challenge #184 - Harry's birthday Summary: Draco wants to do something for Harrys 35th Birthday, but the man himself is not cooperating. Author's Notes: You know, I'm the very first person to admit that Draco is the big party whore, and in June, there was a HUGE party for Draco's 35th, including a comm just for that birthday. Then we get to July, and Harry's 35th, and... crickets. I think there were two of us who answered this challenge. Part of me feels really bad for Harry; poor guy, he saves the wizarding world and his peacock of a boyfriend gets all the love. And then part of me thinks; This is probably exactly the way he'd want it. The Gift

Today has been such a huge day.  First of all, I never get up before seven unless I have no choice.  So today, I was up at six forty five.  Something told me turn on CNN, and they were talking about President Obama doing the eulogy at the funeral of the pastor killed in Charleston.  (he did an amazing job, btw.  If you haven't watched it, you should) And then at 7:01 a.m. PST, the news came down; the Supreme Court ruled in favor of Marriage Equality.  And I started crying.  And I think I've cried almost constantly since.

Then tonight, there's this:


<lj-embed id="67"/>

Pretty damned cool. Pretty. Damned. Cool.

Title: Something Spectacular Author/Artist: oldenuf2nb Word Count: 4620 Pairing: Harry/Draco Rating: NC-17 Created for: slythindor100, Draco’s 35th Birthday Disclaimer: Harry Potter characters are the property of J.K. Rowling and Bloomsbury/Scholastic. No profit is being made, and no copyright infringement is intended. Summary: It’s Draco’s 35th birthday, and he’s less than thrilled. His doting husband knows he’s going to have to come up with something special to change his mind… Written for Slythindor100's Happy Birthday, Draco and this gorgeous pic:
SOMETHING SPECTACULAR
“Draco,” Harry persisted, following his husband through their house. “Drop it, Potter,” Draco shot over his shoulder. ‘Ah, it’s Potter,’ Harry thought, grimacing a little. He was only Potter these days when he was irritating Draco. Clearly, the better part of valour was to take a step back. At least, right then. “Mother has already insisted on our presence at some nonsense at the Manor for dinner, and then I’m going to come home and go to bed. It’s ridiculous, really, to even think about celebrating a birthday at our age.” Harry laughed, even though he hadn’t meant to. “You’re going to be 35, love. It’s not like we’re too old to enjoy a cake and gifts.” Draco paused just before he stepped into the Floo, glaring at Harry. “I’M too old. Now, leave it alone.” He threw a handful of Floo powder onto the fire in their sitting room with more force than usual after calling out the address of his apothecary, stepped into the surging green flames and spun from sight. Harry felt fleeting sympathy for the small crew that worked for him, knowing his husband’s foul mood would probably make for a very long day. Draco had been like this for almost a week, ever since Blaise made a teasing remark about him becoming the ‘senior citizen’ of their group of friends. Not by much, honestly; after all, Harry would be 35 in July, Blaise in October and Pansy, Gods help them all, in December. For Harry, who had always been the youngest of his closest friends, he’d never given it much thought. After all, Hermione and Ron were both already 35 and there hadn’t been any big emotional backlash over their birthdays. But then, they weren’t Draco, either. Harry liked Blaise. Well, most of the time. But he’d begun to pester Draco about his hairline a year before, and he had no idea the kind of hell that unleashed on Harry’s home life. Draco wasn’t vain, honestly. At least, not in comparison to the way he’d been when they were younger. But his hair was a sore point, mostly because Lucius still had a thick head of waist length hair and had begun his own campaign about Draco’s, telling him if ‘he hadn’t ignored his family history (read pure-blood) by cutting it off like a Muggle, he might still have more of it’. It had been only one of the moments during their years together when Harry wanted to curse Lucius into next week. The senior Malfoy never got over the fact Draco chose Harry instead of one of the Greengrass daughter’s, and the ‘there will never be a Malfoy heir’ lament had got to the point it even irritated Narcissa. The fact Draco adopted Teddy and made him the legal Malfoy heir infuriated Lucius. He merely turned his nose up now, however, instead of saying something nasty. The last time he’d called Teddy ‘that werewolf’s cub’ Harry hexed his tongue to the roof of his mouth with both Draco’s and Narcissa’s approval. Harry refused to remove it until Lucius agreed, through nodding, to never say anything like it again. He’d been as good as his word since, even though it was pretty obvious it pained him. At 17, Teddy found Lucius hilarious. He delighted in calling him ‘grandpa’ and watching his face turn bright purple. Harry didn’t find the man nearly as amusing. But Lucius wasn’t today’s issue. Draco was. And what to do to convince his husband that he wasn’t losing his hair, and he wasn’t getting old, and as far as Harry was concerned he was still sex on legs. Okay, so their sex life had fallen off a bit of late, but that was because they were both working such ungodly hours. Draco had just finished a huge order for the wizarding hospital in Australia, and there had been a rash of thefts on Diagon Alley that kept all of the MLE, but most particularly Harry as head Auror, at their jobs late. They’d broken the case just days before, but both he and his husband had been crashing into bed early, catching up on their sleep since. Harry vowed to do something about that on Draco’s birthday. That was when the idea of what to do for Draco’s birthday celebration hit him. He knew Draco wasn’t feeling particularly desirable, which as far as Harry was concerned was the most ludicrous thing in the world. The idea was to convince Draco that, even at thirty five, Harry wanted him more than ever. With a slow smile Hermione often referred to as his ‘scheming grin’, Harry went to make some Floo calls.
******
His birthday dinner at the Manor was the ordeal it had always been, although this time it was exacerbated by his mother’s insistence on including Blaise and Pansy. By the time he’d opened his gifts, (Muggle hair restoring gel from Blaise, damn him, and a lovely leather messenger bag from Pansy) and the triple layer chocolate cake had been proudly presented by the kitchen elves, Draco was beyond ready to go home. He was pleased when over coffee his father presented him with official documents from Gringott’s, designating his as the controlling interest in the Malfoy holdings. It was the traditional Wizarding gift for a pure-blood first born on his thirty fifth birthday. He hadn’t been certain his father would go through with it, honestly, considering the amount of complaining he still did about Harry, even though they’d been together for fifteen years. Draco embraced him, and his father actually hugged him back, something that left both of them pointedly ignoring the lump in their throats. At one time, living to thirty-five had been outside of Draco’s comprehension. Even though he’d been feeling old for the last week, he couldn’t say he was sorry to have reached the milestone. When Harry stood after finishing his coffee and kissed an extremely smug looking Narcissa on the cheek, Draco was already giving him a narrow-eyed look. His husband, looking carelessly handsome in his wool slacks and button down, a nod to his mother’s preference that they still ‘dress’ for meals, handed Narcissa a small box and then crossed to Draco. The look on his face left Draco feeling less than pleased. Harry, on the other hand, gave him a meltingly sweet smile. “Don’t glare at me,” Harry murmured, taking his hand and bringing it to his lips. Lucius huffed but Harry lingered, pressing his lips to Draco’s knuckles, his tongue briefly stroking the back of his third finger just above his ring. He then bent, his mouth hovering near Draco’s ear. “Your mother is going to give you that in half an hour,” he said. “I love you, but I don’t trust you to wait that long.” Draco opened his mouth to complain, but Harry cut him off with a deep, slow kiss that had Draco’s toes curling in his boots. When he finally pulled back Lucius was vibrating with annoyance, and Draco was breathless. “I’ll see you in a little bit.” With that, he turned and Apparated on the spot. “What…?” Draco looked over to find Narcissa humming lightly, a soft smile curling her lips. “Mother?” “Thirty minutes, Draco, and not a moment before. Have another bite of cake.” “Draco, sometime can you get hold of Potter’s invisibility cloak for me?” Pansy asked sweetly. “If that kiss is any indication of what goes on in your bedroom, I want to sneak in and watch.” “Oh, for Merlin’s sakes, Pansy,” Lucius moaned. “Have you no consideration for my digestion?” Pansy gave him a bright smile, and Draco began stealing glimpses at the clock on the mantle. When thirty minutes had passed, and not a second before, Draco’s mother stood and crossed to him, leaning down to kiss his cheek. “Happy Birthday, my darling,” she whispered and handed him the small box, then stood back with a knowing smile to watch him open it. It was black velvet, encircled by a green satin ribbon. Very posh for Harry, honestly, and it looked like a jewelry box, but if his husband had given him jewelry, why in the world would he leave first? He yanked the ribbon free and lifted the lid. Inside was a small silver token embossed with a snake, a piece of parchment slipped beneath it. He frowned at it. “What is this?” he murmured. “Read the note,” Narcissa prompted. Draco pulled it from the box and unfolded it. “Love of my life,” it read. “This is a Portkey, and it will activate almost instantly. There will be instructions when you arrive. I love you. H.” Draco looked up at his mother, but her knowing smile remained. He didn’t have time to question her, because the unmistakable sensation of traveling by Portkey tugged just behind his navel, and he spared a moment to hope he didn’t land on his arse as his parent’s sitting room spun away. He knew he’d traveled a fair distance because of the length of time he was in the midst of the swirling cyclone. When he landed he stumbled, and was instantly ready to tear a strip off of his husband, until the world settled and he straightened. He was in what he assumed was a hotel room, and a sumptuous one, at that. There was a massive king sized bed in front of him, draped in gray satin, and through a doorway he could see an elaborate sitting room with black leather furniture. His eyes were drawn back to the bed before he could consider exploring, and to the card propped on the foot. Your attire for this evening is hanging in the armoire. Please change. Don’t dally. A gentleman will be knocking on the door in exactly fifteen minutes to escort you to your next destination. “High handed git,” Draco muttered, but the truth was he was agonizingly curious about where he was. He went to the heavily draped window and looked out, gasping a bit when he saw the Eiffel Tower majestically lit in the distance. Paris was his favorite place on earth, and Harry knew it. His smile matched the lift of his pounding heart as he crossed to the large, black lacquered armoire. He wasn’t sure what he’d been expecting, but it wasn’t what he found. Hanging there was a pair of his favorite denim slacks; they made his hips look narrow and his legs almost impossibly long and his arse look amazing. Next to them was one of his tight v-necked silk t-shirts in a soft gray, and the black leather jacket Harry had purchased for him for Christmas. It was butter soft and made his shoulders looked broad, something he feared they’d never really been on their own, despite his husband’s protest to the contrary. Beneath all of it were his favorite pair of black boots with silver chains around the heel. Draco stared at the combination thoughtfully, then began to shrug out of the robes he’d worn to the Manor. He changed quickly, then found his small travel shaving kit on the counter in the sumptuous bathroom. There was no time to shave and as he hadn’t really had the desire in several days, his chin was covered with stubble as long and as dark as it ever was. He barely had time to run a comb through his hair and splash on some of his cologne before, right on schedule, a knock sounded at the door. He took one last glance at himself in the mirror, just enough to notice that the shirt made his eyes stand out, then crossed to the door. An older gentleman stood there in a smart black suit, and he bowed slightly. “If you’ll follow me, please, Monsieur Malfoy?” he said, his English softened with a French accent. “Lead the way,” Draco said, his heart beating rapidly in anticipation. He was thoroughly enjoying himself. Harry knew him so well. A trip to Paris for his birthday was the perfect gift. Draco vowed to kiss him senseless when he saw him. He followed the man onto an elevator, and when he turned to face the door he realized he was in a penthouse suite. He also saw the name Hadrian’s Palace embossed on the inside next to the rows of buttons for the floors. He swallowed a startled gasp. It was a wizarding hotel, one he and Harry had read about in a travel brochure. Right in the heart of Paris, invisible to Muggles, it was a gay establishment named for the Emperor Hadrian, who had famously kept a much younger male lover name Antinous. He’d been so in love that when the young man drowned, the inconsolable emperor began a religion in his honor that was practiced for hundreds of years. Draco had shown the pamphlet for this hotel to Harry, and they’d both thought it would be a wonderful place to go if they ever had the time. Apparently his husband decided his thirty fifth birthday was the time. They arrived in the lobby, and Draco looked around avidly. It was all marble and gold, busts of the emperor and his famous lover holding court on a marble dais right in the center under an arching golden dome. He followed his guide across the wide expanse, gratified by the smiling glances he got from other men in various places in the lobby. One young man didn’t even pretend to hide his admiration, just stared avidly as he passed, and it worked wonders for Draco’s ego. They arrived at another elevator, and the man produced a small golden key, which he inserted into a lock and turned. The doors slid open silently, and the man bowed with a slight smile, handing Draco another small piece of parchment. “Have a lovely evening,” he said, and Draco returned his smile, stepping onto the elevator. Before the doors even slid closed, he was opening his note. Go to the last seat at the bar on the left. “Huh,” Draco muttered. Clearly, he was headed to a bar. But the ride down in the elevator seemed much longer than merely going down a floor or two, and there were no markings inside to indicate where he might be going. By the time the doors slid open, he was breathless with anticipation. The first thing that overwhelmed his senses was the sound of music, particularly the bass, which throbbed beneath his feet. Directly across from him was an arched doorway, and lettering inscribed in the marble read ‘The Temple of Antinous’. Draco grinned. This was perhaps the most exclusive gay club in Paris, entered by invitation only. Clearly, the key upstairs had been his. Never in his wildest imaginings did he think even Harry could pull off an invitation to this club. But then he realized he should have known better. Harry would be invited anywhere. He just usually refused to use his fame to garner invites. The fact that he’d done something he ordinarily would never do, for him, caused warmth grow in Draco’s chest. He moved forward, his eyes avid. The club was so crowded there was no way to know what the décor looked like, other than it was very dark, with elaborate light displays and beautiful young men made up to look like statues, wearing nothing more than white g-strings, dancing on marble pedestals placed at random places throughout the room. There were also dozens of gorgeous men writhing to the beat of the music, some shirtless, others clad all in leather. They seemed to part in front of Draco as he passed, but the admiration in their eyes as they watched him pass couldn’t be denied. He even felt a touch or two graze his arse, but he was too delighted to be offended. Here, he was clearly still very much desired, and even Harry couldn’t have managed to engineer that display. There was an open seat right where Harry said there would be at the end of the bar, and Draco slid onto it, smiling into the eyes of the waiting, shirtless bartender. “Hello,” he said. The man nodded, grinning, and handed him another note. Enjoy, Love. Draco read. He frowned slightly and looked around for Harry, but didn’t see him anywhere. He turned back to the bartender, who without taking an order set a small, chilled crystal fluted glass in front of Draco, then lifted a bottle shaped like a fairy, her wings spread as if to take off in flight, from beneath the bar. Draco’s breath caught. He loved Absinthe. He didn’t allow himself to drink it often, but it appeared his husband had ordered this for him. Draco watched in delight as the bartender poured a shot of the brilliant green liquor into the glass, then set a slotted spoon on the rim and placed a single, glimmering sugar cube on top of it. He moved the glass to a small fountain of ice water in the corner, and Draco watched avidly as the slow, steady stream of water melted the cube and turned the brilliant green a soft, cloudy mint color. When the sugar was gone, the bartender placed a small nearly transparent china saucer on the bar, then presented the glass with a slight flourish and a sexy smile. As Draco watched, a beautiful ghostly fairy lifted from the glass to pose for a moment, and then she flew to his face, gently touched his lips, and vanished with a smile. Delighted, Draco lifted the glass and took a sip. He sighed in pleasure. The faintly herbal taste, combined with a slight nip of licorice and the sweetness of the sugar, was sublime. He knew that the wormwood of the old days had been more pronounced, and the hallucinogenic affects much more apparent, but Draco loved the flavor, and the slightly euphoric buzz that zinged along his nerve endings. As he sipped and began to look around the bar, he realized with a surge of satisfaction that he was being eyed by more than one of the men nearby. It had been years since he felt the heady rush of being openly desired by strangers, and he smiled, closing his eyes, savoring his drink. When he finished the first, he ordered another. Half way through it, when a hard chest pressed against his back, Draco felt a moment of alarm and stiffened, about to tell off whomever had taken the liberty without even addressing him. But then he caught a whiff of familiar cologne and the press of lips against his nape, and he softened into the hardness behind him, angling his head slightly to the side, sighing when teeth gently scraped his skin. “Hello, beautiful,” a deep voice said against his ear. “Enjoying your drink?” Draco hummed. “So very much,” he answered. An arm slipped around his waist and Draco looked down, saw the black silk sleeve rolled up to reveal a strong forearm sprinkled with black hair. He recognized the shirt. He’d bought it for Harry for his last birthday and he loved the way the expensive fabric conformed to the muscles of his arms and chest. Just the thought of it made desire begin to thrum low in his belly. He let his head drop back onto the square shoulder, nuzzling his forehead against Harry’s cheek. “Want to dance?” “Absolutely.” Draco took the square hand that was offered and allowed himself to be pulled into the middle of the dance floor. He watched Harry moving through the crowd ahead of him, black shirt unbuttoned down his tawny chest, black hair disreputable and yet somehow perfect. When Harry finally found room for both of them and encircled Draco’s ribcage with his hands, pulling him in, Draco gave in to the desire to sink his long fingers into that mop of thick hair. It was soft and clung to his fingers, and he moved in to press his forehead to his husband’s and let Harry move him to the music. Harry had never considered himself much of a dancer, but he was wrong. With just a touch he turned Draco, his arms around his waist, his face against Draco’s nape as he pressed his erection against Draco’s arse. Draco reached back, grabbing Harry’s hip, moving against him to the driving pulse of the beat. Oh, he’d missed this. A beautifully built young man moved close in front of Draco, and he had a lovely smile. He eased closer, one hand reaching out to slide his fingers down Draco’s cheek. Draco felt Harry stiffen behind him and he squeezed his hip in reassurance. “You and your friend care for a third?” the man shouted so as to be heard above the music. “The two of you are hot as hell.” Draco gave him a slight smile and lifted his left hand, and the rotating lights caught in the carved facets of the platinum ring on his third finger. The man shrugged regretfully and moved away, and Draco turned in Harry’s arms, lifting his around Harry’s neck. From this close, Harry’s eyes were the color of the absinthe before the sugar, bright shining green. Harry’s hand dropped down to cup his arse and Draco pressed his erection against the thigh Harry slid between his legs. “Ready for me?” Harry said, pressing his forehead to Draco’s. Draco smiled, aligning his body with Harry’s from chin to toes as they moved to the beat. “I’ve been ready for you since I was fourteen years old,” Draco breathed. “I just didn’t know it for what it was at the time.” He heard Harry draw in a deep breath, and then his lips were taken in a desperate, consuming kiss. The jerk of Apparition didn’t even interrupt their kiss, and when they arrived in their room, Draco found himself on his back on the bed with Harry between his legs. “I want you so much,” Harry said against Draco’s throat. “I’m yours, Harry. Always yours.” The first time they didn’t even get their clothes off. Trousers were opened, pants shoved aside, cocks gripped in desperate fists and wanked to explosive conclusion. The second time, once the desperation was eased, Harry stripped Draco slowly, kissing each inch of exposed skin, making love to every curve of his long body. He stroked Draco’s chest and sucked his nipples, slid his hand up a long pale thigh and slipped slick fingers between his legs, behind his balls. When he pressed his thumb against Draco’s hole, it slid inside with barely a burn. “I don’t need that,” Draco said against Harry’s lips. “I just need you.” “I need you, too,” Harry said, lifting Draco’s leg to his shoulder and bending him double to kiss him deeply, pushing inside in one slow slide. Draco gasped, his back arching. Gods, he was so full, so full of Harry, and it was perfect. He hitched his other leg over Harry’s hip, wrapped his arms around Harry’s neck, and hung on for the ride. Where before he’d been all gentleness, now Harry thrust into Draco, bordering on rough, and Draco loved it. He moaned, trying to thrust back, but Harry grabbed his hips in his hands, holding him still as he moved inside of him. The angle wasn’t quite right, and Draco mewled, his nails digging into Harry’s forearms. “I need to move,” he gasped. “Harry, please. My dad passed away this afternoon. He was ninety years old, and lived a long full life. He and my mother were married sixty eight years, and he adored her every one of those years. They have five children, nine grandchildren and eleven great-grandchildren, all of whom thought he was the finest man they'd ever met. Because he was. I'll miss him desperately, but I thank God for taking away his pain.

Just a quick mention of something that's a particular pet peeve of mine.  Around the holidays, there are lots of gift exchange fests.  It sort of starts out with Glompfest, which is near and dear to my heart because the gifts are for the readers and without them where would we writers be, honestly?  There is HDErised and Mini-fest and others I know I'm leaving out (Please forgive me - I honestly can't keep up with them all).  But if you've signed up for a fest, and someone has gone to the trouble of creating a gift for you, and you don't leave a comment?  All that does is make the creator feel like you must not have liked your gift.  And that's kind of a lousy feeling.

I know we're all busy and that life can get away from us.  Trust me, I know.  Just... if you signed up for a fest, take two minutes a day to check the postings.  And if you only say, 'I really like this' or 'thank you so much', that's infinitely better than silence.

For those of you who have met her, my lovely daughter got married Friday night. It was a gorgeous ceremony, a wonderful party, and a lovely time was had by all. The hotel is a gorgeous old place called the Davenport here in downtown Spokane, and it's a perfect venue. The front desk of the hotel had a bit of 'head up our collective ass' disease, and I'm still working on that, but otherwise it was wonderful. This is my lovely girl and her handsome new hubby, and they are currently enjoying the sun in Cancun. Which is nice, considering it's currently 22 degrees here at home! In other news, I now have this wedding to pay off so I'm going to be selling off my portfolio. I'll be posting the pics available here over the next few days, and if you see anything you want, or would like to commission something, please let me know. I will be available for that, when I'm not writing a sequel to An Reason To Believe, for the foreseeable future!!

I woke up this morning to find out that The Secrets of Neverwood Anthology is a finalist for the 2014 Rainbow Awards!! This is really humbling when you see the company , and I are keeping. J.p. Barnaby, who is a good friend, writes an absolutely gut wrenching novel. Her 'A Heart for Robbie' broke me in the best of ways, and when you find out it was written from the perspective of a mom who lost her own precious daughter to heart disease, it's all the more remarkable. Amy Lane is another for whom hurt/comfort is a staple, and her 'Behind the Curtain' is one of my all time favorite books. Omorphi, by Cody Kennedy is an engrossing YA book about a high school jock and his androgynous boyfriend, and I love the way her characters were so real to me that I didn't want a 1400 page book to end. Heidi Cullinan's Tough Love is the third in one of my all time favorite series, and her description of main character Chenco's nightly transformation into Caramela, his drag alter ego, is fascinating. Rick R. Reed, who wrote Dinner At Home, is a first class foodie and awesome cook for his husband, Bruce, and I want to try the recipes included in this fun book. There is some absolutely amazing fiction being written in the m/m genre, and being considered for this pretigious award is just... humbling. Check out the lists. And if you aren't already reading original gay fiction, I think you'll find it's pretty damned amazing!
